title: For Sale:  (SOLD) 1869/71 Swiss Vetterli, 41 Swiss, w/ accessories. $350
postcontent: Bolt marked 1880 converted to centerfire (rimfire pin included) and is reversible back to rimfire if you ever find some original 41 Swiss. Only permanent modification is a small hole (pluggable) drilled into bolt-face to accommodate the firing pin. Fully functional rifle: ejects, feeds, and magazine works correctly! Not bad for 130 years old! Walnut stock restored by non-abrasive methods and painstakingly finished with raw linseed oil (original finish). Hardware and receiver left in the original “white steel,” without use of abrasives. Cartouches and marks are intact. Barrel has browned with age. Bore is dark (in grooves) with light pitting but good sharp rifling. Barrel has been pressure lapped using the Ross Seifreid method. It shoots as well as the sights allow. Barrel slugged nominally .429-.430; twist rate works optimally with heavy 44 Mag bullets. The Lee 310 grainer is great. I have fifty 8mm Lebel cases cut and formed in Lee 41 Swiss dies (included in package) to go with it. Cleaning rod is a homemade look-alike. She’s wearing an old M1907 sling, which works as well as any on such a long rifle. 41 Swiss is approximately equal to 44 Mag in power IMR 4759 works, but I have used FF Black Powder and American Pioneer Replica Blackpowder as well. I have enjoyed her, but now I hope somebody will enjoy her as much as I did. Antique; can ship to doorstep with copy of driver’s license. She’s clean and covered with rust-inhibitor. FTF or USPS shipping $20.

title: For Sale:  (SOLD) Carl Gustav Model of 1896 in 6.5x55 Swedish. $225
postcontent:
Brilliant fire-blued sight-spring. Stock a bit rough but no crack or splits even in the handguard. The arsenal disk indicates almost a perfect barrel/throat condition, which is somewhat unusual. Barrel does indeed look excellent and it shoots very well. Around 1.5 MOA with quality handloads.
6.5x55 is available just about anywhere a good selection of rifle ammunition is found (BassPro). Remington loads it as does PrviPartizan of which I can sell you all you want for $13 per 20 round box locally.
The sights are calibrated for 300 meters, so I bought a taller front post and filed it down so it’s on a 100 yards. I have original sight. They are very good adjustable sights. The overall quality and condition of this rifle is very good. No rust, though a lot of blueing has worn away. Trigger is a somewhat heavy 2-stage. The Swedes made these during peacetime with the greatest attention to quality and condition. No other Mauser is made as well, is as smooth, or is chambered in as good a caliber. I have the very basic carrying strap, sight hood, cleaning rod, stripper-clips ($1 ea), and bayonet ($25) for it as well. 
The small ring Mausers make superlative sporterizing candidates for Eastern game like Whitetails. 6.5x55 is a truly superlative cartridge with excellent range, great accuracy, and moderate recoil. Off-the-shelf parts are available for this rifle that can take you anywhere you want to go. I even have an inletted walnut sporter stock for it for $50
I have Mojo Aperture rear sight for this rifle for $50. 6.5x55 Reloading dies for $20. 
FTF locally or USPS shipping to FFL or legal Ohioan with signed drivers’ license $20.

title: For Sale:  Beretta 1934 9mmCorto (.380) dated 1942
postcontent: The Beretta 1934 9mm Corto (.380cal) is well known among shooters and collectors alike to be a durable, reliable, great little gun. I’ve owned probably a dozen of these in the last 50 years, shot them all and never remember a misfire of any kind. They are easy to break down for cleaning and are all built of  very strong tool-steel. No cheap plastic will be found in a ’34 like in today’s small concealed carry .380s. This particular gun, WWII era, is dated 1942 and is in very good condition. It has developed some bluing wear along the sharp edges as is to be expected for this old a gun. See the photos. But otherwise appears to have been very well taken care of. The rifling is strong and sharp with only a faint hint of the satin look that seems to develop even in the best of  barrels of these older guns. It has none of that awful pitting that is seen an a lot of WWII guns subjected to corrosive ammo and poor cleaning. It is a great and accurate little shooter. You can spend your money on one of those trouble prone steel/plastic new ones, or twice as much as I’m asking on an all steel Walther PPK or similar weapon. But you won't find a more reliable weapon than the 1934. Yours for $350 cash only and meet in a public place.
